	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_70634"><p>That's right. My current view of this is that you <em>should</em> be taken back to "write test", even though you'll be writing a stubbed class thereafter. (Maybe the framework can be smart enough to recognize that you need to write the stubbed class, and tell you as much. But nominally, you'll still end up in "write test".) Why? Because in order to proceed to "hack, hack", you need to actually provide a new test which fails.</p><p>That's just my current understanding of the vaporware. Alternative interpretations are welcom<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
		
	
	</div>
